<subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-of-composite-solids" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Volume of Composite Solids</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.8 Volume
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the volume of composite solids. Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a composite solid as a three-dimensional shape made up of two or more simple solids. Understand when to add volumes (solids joined together) and when to subtract volumes (parts removed, such as holes).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify the simple solids that make up a composite solid. Calculate the volume of each part separately using the appropriate formula and add or subtract as needed.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving composite solids such as containers with cylindrical holes, structures combining cylinders and cones, and objects with hemispheres attached.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/volume-of-composite-solids.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/step-by-step-guide_volume-of-composite-solids.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Constructing Real-World Objects</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Work in groups of at least four members
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p>
                    Building blocks or 3D shape cut-outs (foam, paper nets, toy blocks), rulers or measuring tapes, worksheets for drawings and calculations, volume formula sheet
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate among groups, ensuring students build structures correctly. Ask probing questions: <q>What shapes did you use? How will you find the total volume?</q> For struggling groups: <q>Let us identify the shapes together. What is this shape? What is the formula?</q> For early finishers: <q>Can you build a structure with a hole or removed part?</q> Guide students to articulate that a composite solid is made up of two or more simple solids and we add or subtract their volumes.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p>What is a composite solid?</p></li>
                        <li><p>How do we find the volume of a composite solid?</p></li>
                        <li><p>When do we add volumes? When do we subtract?</p></li>
                        <li><p>What real-world objects are composite solids?</p></li>
                        <li><p>How can we break down complex shapes into simpler solids?</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            Identify 2<ndash/>3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
    </axiom>


<activity xml:id="auto_txd7cj1w">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_01ujwexz">
                Constructing a real-world object using basic solids (cylinder, cube, cone, hemisphere, etc.) and calculate the total volume.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_43b2fbwr">
                <ul xml:id="auto_ty4vgoay">
                    <li xml:id="auto_rb8959l0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ivnq0qlg">
                            <m>\textbf{Materials needed:}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_o5jg0b45">
                            

                           🔹 Building blocks or 3D shape cut-outs (foam, paper nets, or toy blocks)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ascxd062">
                           🔹 Rulers or measuring tapes
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_q1f8oj21">

                           🔹 Worksheets for drawings and calculations
                        </p> 
                        <p xml:id="auto_jw164fhx">
                       🔹 Volume formula sheet
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tc044ozd">
                        <p xml:id="auto_lzcndpz2">
                            Review volume formulas for Cube/cuboid, cylinder, cone, sphere, Hemisphere, triangular prisms and pyramids.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_5l05dyus">
                        <p xml:id="auto_0irxefzs">
                            Work in groups of atleast four members.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_spdso3wv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ba5qx0ya">
                           🔹 Build UP a structure using 2 to 3 shapes. For example 
                        </p>
                    
                        <p xml:id="auto_s91x1j3l">
                           🔹 A lighthouse (cylinder + cone)
                        </p>
                    
                        <p xml:id="auto_mqzw7z6y">
                            An ice cream cone (cone + hemisphere)
                        </p>
                    
                        <p xml:id="auto_pls3ni1z">
                           🔹 A mailbox (cuboid + half-cylinder)
                        </p>
                      <p xml:id="auto_xc8d7sny">
                           🔹 A robot body (cuboid + cylinder arms + sphere head)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_18tcfgva">
                           🔹 After building up draw the structure, label the parts and measure dimensions. Then alculate the volume of each solid part using the correct formulas.
                        </p>
                    
                        <p xml:id="auto_oxfc5yny">
                           🔹 Then they add all volumes to get the total.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <p xml:id="auto_owwf0y7p">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_zyme0am5">
       A composite solid is a three-dimensional shape made up of two or more simple solids (such as cubes, cylinders, cones, spheres, prisms, and pyramids). To find the volume of a composite solid, the volumes of the individual solids are calculated and then either added or subtracted, depending on the situation.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_lho9wiij">
        <ul xml:id="auto_ssfxmz0o">
            <li xml:id="auto_3rclabap">
                <p xml:id="auto_5cv93i3m">
                    

                  Identify the simple solids that make up the composite solid
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_iut47l84">
                <p xml:id="auto_in1bta8g">
                    

                 Calculate the volume of each individual solid using the appropriate formula
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_u80du7cc">
                <p xml:id="auto_0mzuzoaz">
                    Add or subtract the volumes i.e:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_15w885ey">
                   🔹 If the solids are joined together, add their volumes.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nvpjw4mx">

                    🔹 If a part of one solid is removed (e.g., a hole), subtract its volume from the total.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_r9mrozpe">
                <p xml:id="auto_ci3g18fq">
                    
                    Examples of Composite Solids include  Cylinder with a Hemisphere on Top, Rectangular Prism with a Cylindrical Hole etc.
                </p>
            </li>

        </ul>
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A solid is formed by mounting a hemisphere on top of a cylinder. The cylinder has a height of <m>14</m> cm and a diameter of <m>12</m> cm. Find the total volume of the solid. Give your answer in terms of <m>\pi</m> and correct to two decimal places.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Radius of the cylinder:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>r = \frac{12}{2} = 6 \;\text{cm}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Volume of the cylinder:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>V = \amp \pi r^2 h</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi (6)^2 (14)</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 504\pi</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Volume of the hemisphere:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> V = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{2}{3}\pi (6)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{2}{3}\pi (216)</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 144\pi</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Total volume:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>V = 504\pi + 144\pi</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m> V = 648\pi \;\text{cm}^3</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                In decimal form:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>V \approx 2036.73\; \text{cm}^3</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Formalizing Composite Solid Volume</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Whole class
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> All composite solids require adding volumes. <alert>Clarification:</alert> If a part is removed (like a hole), you subtract its volume.</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> I can use any formula. <alert>Clarification:</alert> You must use the correct formula for each individual solid.</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> I only need to calculate one volume. <alert>Clarification:</alert> You must calculate the volume of each solid part separately, then add or subtract.</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> Composite solids are too complex. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Break them down into simpler solids you already know.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Individual, then pairs for checking
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Walk through the worked example on the board step-by-step: first calculate the prism volume, then the cylinder volume, then subtract. Allow students to attempt practice problems independently. Emphasise the three-step process: identify, calculate, combine.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_ftrnu12n">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_moia1m60">
                A rectangular prism has dimensions length = 10 cm, width = 6 cm, and height = 15 cm. A cylindrical hole of radius 2 cm passes vertically through the entire height of the prism.

                Find the volume of the remaining solid after the hole is removed.
            </p>
             <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      <latex-image label="Cone-cylinder-exercise-one">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw an ellipse
            \draw[dashed,gray,thick] (-4.5,2.6) ellipse (1.5cm and 0.3cm);
            \draw[gray,thick] (-4.5,4) ellipse (1.5cm and 0.3cm);
            \shade[dashed,ball color=blue!50!white,thick] (-4.5,4) ellipse (1.5cm and 0.3cm);
            \shade[dashed,ball color=black!30!white,thick] (-4.5,2.6) ellipse (1.5cm and 0.3cm);

            %Draw the cylinder
            \draw[dashed,gray,thick] (-6,2.6) -- (-6,4);
            \draw[dashed,gray,thick] (-3,2.6) -- (-3,4);

            %Coordinates for the cuboid
            \coordinate (A) at (-6.32,4.35);
            \coordinate (B) at (-2.32,4.33);
            \coordinate (C) at (-2.32,3.03);
            \coordinate (D) at (-6.32,3.01);
            \coordinate (E) at (-6.64,3.61);
            \coordinate (F) at (-2.76,3.63);
            \coordinate (G) at (-2.76,2.23);
            \coordinate (H) at (-6.66,2.17);

            %Radius of the cylinder
            \coordinate (P) at (-4.5,4);
            \coordinate (Q) at (-3,4);
            \draw(P)--(Q);
            \node[above right] at (P) {$r= 2\,cm$};
            \node at (-5,2) {$10\,cm$};
            \node at (-2,2.5) {$6\,cm$};
            \node[right] at (-2.2,3.5) {$15\,cm$};

            %Draw the cuboid
            \draw[blue,thick] (E)--(F)--(G)--(H)--cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (A)--(B)--(F)--(E)--cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (B)--(C)--(G)--(F)--cycle;

            \shade[cyan,opacity=0.5] (C)--(D)--(H)--(G)--cycle;
            \shade[ball color=red!50!white,opacity=0.5] (C)--(G)--(F)--(B)--cycle;
            \shade[ball color=orange!50!white,opacity=0.5] (A)--(B)--(C)--(D)--cycle;
            \shade[ball color=red!50!white,opacity=0.5] (A)--(D)--(H)--(E)--cycle;

            \draw[dashed,blue,thick] (A)--(D);
            \draw[dashed,blue,thick] (H)--(D);
            \draw[dashed,blue,thick] (D)--(C);
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>  
    </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_h5l2t7wr">
                Step 1: Find the Volume of the Rectangular Prism
                <md>
                    <mrow>V_{\text{prism}} =\amp \text{length} \times \text{width }\times \text{height} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \, 10 \, \text{cm} \times 6 \, \text{cm} \times 15 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 900 \,  \text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                </md>
                Step 2: Find the Volume of the Cylindrical Hole
                <md>
                    <mrow>V_{\text{cylinder}} = \amp \pi r^2h </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 3.14 \times \, (2 \,\text{cm})^2  \times 15 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 188.4 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
                Step 3: Find the Volume of the Remaining Solid
                <md>
                    <mrow> V_{\text{Total volume remaining}}  = \amp V_{\text{prism}} - V_{\text{cylinder}} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp (900 -188.4)\, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 711.6 \, \text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                </md>
                The volume of the remaining solid after the hole is removed is <m>711.6 \text{cm}^3</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Individual
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Exit Ticket</title>
                <p>
                    Students complete questions 4 and 5 individually.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key (Teacher Reference)</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p>Cube side <m>= 12</m> cm (diameter of sphere). <m>V_{\text{cube}} = 12^3 = 1728\,\text{cm}^3</m>. <m>V_{\text{sphere}} = \frac{4}{3}\pi(6)^3 \approx 904.32\,\text{cm}^3</m>. Space <m>= 1728 - 904.32 = 823.68\,\text{cm}^3</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p><m>V_{\text{prism}} = 10 \times 6 \times 15 = 900\,\text{cm}^3</m>. <m>V_{\text{pyramid}} = \frac{1}{3} \times 10 \times 10 \times 8 = 266.67\,\text{cm}^3</m>. Total <m>= 900 + 266.67 = 1166.67\,\text{cm}^3</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_j1nsbm9e">
        <m>\textbf{Exercise}</m>
    </p>
